########################################################################################   OVERVIEW    #########################################################################


# Valgrind is an instrumentation framework for building dynamic analysis tools. There are Valgrind tools that can automatically detect many memory management 
# and threading bugs, and profile programs in detail


########################################################################################   CALLGRIND    ########################################################################


# Display performance statistics!!
#
# To use:
# 
# 	valgrind --dsymutil=yes --tool=callgrind
# 
# it will produce a callgrind.out.PID ( PID - process ID of the program	that ran ). To analyze this file use the tool :
# 
# 	callgrind_annotate callgrind.out.PID
# 
# which will tell which functions used the most instructions to run, sorted from highest to lowest. From this the functions that need optimization can be 
# obtained. Now to enter further in give also the source file :
# 
# 	callgrind_annotate callgrind.out.PID source/file/path
# 
# And the number of instructions each line caused will be displayed. This way the most expensive lines can be noticed and dealt with
# 
# To create the output file in a different destination use :
# 
# 		--callgrind-out-file=file/path/


###################################################################################   CACHEGRIND   ############################################################################


# Analyzing memory access!!
#
# To use:
# 
# 	valgrind --tool=cachegrind test/file/path
# 
# It will produce a cachegrind.out.PID ( PID - process ID of the program that ran ). To analyze this file use the tool :
# 
# 	cg_annotate callgrind.out.PID
# 
# Use the show option to get a smaller output :
# 
# 	cg_annotate --show=Dr,Dw callgrind.out.PID
# 
# 	Dw - memory write, Dr - memory read



